  <p>Federal income tax gets the most attention in paycheck calculations, but state income tax is often what makes the biggest difference between locations. The federal calculation is the same regardless of where you live; the state calculation is not. Move from a state with no income tax to a state with a 9% top rate, and the paycheck difference on the same gross salary can be $400–$700 per month or more. That's a meaningful number to leave out of any location or salary comparison.</p>

  <h2>Why state taxes change the take-home calculation significantly</h2>
  <p>State income tax is applied in addition to federal income tax, Social Security, and Medicare. On a $75,000 gross salary, federal income tax after the standard deduction might run around $8,000–$9,000 per year in effective taxes, depending on filing status. State income tax in a high-rate state could add another $4,000–$6,000. In a no-income-tax state, it adds zero.</p>
  <p>That difference — $4,000–$6,000 annually, or $330–$500 monthly — is real take-home pay. It's also often invisible in headline salary comparisons, which quote gross figures with no mention of the tax environment. Two people earning $75,000 can have meaningfully different monthly budgets depending on where they live, and state tax is a major reason why. The <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator.html">Take-Home Pay Calculator</a> includes state income tax as an input — use it to model your specific situation rather than relying on rough rules of thumb.</p>

  <h2>States with no income tax</h2>
  <p>Nine states currently impose no state income tax on wages: Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire (investment income only), South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, and Wyoming. For W-2 employees in these states, state income tax simply isn't part of the take-home calculation.</p>
  <p>Living in one of these states adds roughly 3–7% of gross salary back to take-home pay compared to a mid-rate state, and 7–12% compared to a high-rate state, depending on income level. On a $100,000 salary, that range represents $7,000–$12,000 per year in additional take-home pay — before any cost-of-living differences are factored in.</p>
  <p>It's worth noting that some no-income-tax states offset revenue through higher sales taxes, property taxes, or other mechanisms. The paycheck calculation is cleaner, but the full financial picture — particularly for homeowners — should account for those other taxes.</p>

  <h2>States with high income tax rates</h2>
  <p>California, New York, New Jersey, Oregon, and Minnesota consistently rank among the highest-rate states — each uses graduated brackets that can reach double-digit percentages at upper income levels. The specific rates change, so verify current brackets before planning. These top rates apply to higher incomes, but even moderate incomes in these states face substantially higher effective rates than in low- or no-tax states.</p>
  <p>High-rate states are often high-cost states, which compounds the comparison problem: a higher gross salary offer in California doesn't translate to proportionally higher take-home compared to a lower gross in Texas. In many cases, the California gross has to be meaningfully higher just to break even in net monthly pay. This is one of the most common miscalculations when comparing job offers across state lines — and it's one the <a href="/articles/compare-job-offers-take-home-pay.html">job offer comparison framework</a> is designed to handle directly.</p>

  <h2>Flat-rate states vs. bracketed states</h2>
  <p>State income tax systems fall into three structures: no tax, flat rate, and graduated brackets. Flat-rate states apply the same percentage to all taxable income regardless of how much you earn — Illinois (4.95%), Michigan (4.25%), and Pennsylvania (3.07%) are common examples. Graduated-bracket states, like the federal system, apply lower rates to lower income and higher rates to higher income.</p>
  <p>The structure matters for planning because it changes how marginal increases in income are taxed. In a flat-rate state, each additional dollar of income costs the same percentage in state tax regardless of your total income. In a bracketed state, moving to a higher income level can push some of your income into a higher bracket. The Take-Home Pay Calculator handles both structures automatically, so you don't have to decode the rate structure yourself.</p>

  <h2>Remote work and where you owe tax</h2>
  <p>Remote work introduced a complication that didn't exist when everyone worked in the same city as their employer: the question of which state's tax applies to your income. The general rule is that you owe income tax in the state where you perform the work — your state of residence. But some states, including New York, apply "convenience of the employer" rules: if you work remotely out of your own convenience rather than employer necessity, your income may be taxed by the employer's state even if you live elsewhere.</p>
  <p>If you work remotely for an employer in a high-tax state while living in a no-income-tax state, you may or may not owe tax to the employer's state depending on those specific rules. This is a real calculation that can affect hundreds of dollars per month in take-home pay, and it's worth understanding before accepting a remote position — especially when the employer's headquarters and your home state have meaningfully different tax rates.</p>

  <h2>State tax plus cost of living: the full picture</h2>
  <p>State tax is one component of the location-adjusted compensation picture. Housing, which is often the largest monthly expense, is the other. High-income-tax states are often high-cost-of-living states. Low-income-tax states vary considerably — Texas is low-tax but not uniformly low-cost; New Hampshire is low-tax and medium-cost; Florida varies widely by city.</p>
  <p>The honest comparison for location decisions is after-tax income minus cost of living. Two locations that look identical in gross salary and state tax rate can differ significantly when housing is included. A $90,000 salary in Austin and a $90,000 salary in Seattle have similar federal tax treatment but meaningfully different housing markets. Running the take-home calculation is step one — building the full budget is step two.</p>

  <h2>Modeling your actual take-home</h2>
  <p>The fastest way to get an accurate state-adjusted take-home is to use the <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator.html">Take-Home Pay Calculator</a> with the correct state selected. The calculator handles state-specific rates and brackets so you're not working from averages or memory. Run it once for each location or salary scenario you're comparing.</p>
  <p>For income tax rates at the federal level, the <a href="/tax-bracket-calculator.html">Tax Bracket Calculator</a> provides a breakdown of which brackets apply to your income — useful when you want to understand the marginal rate on a raise or bonus rather than just the effective rate on total income. When comparing two locations side by side, combine the take-home output with a cost-of-living estimate for housing and transport in each city to arrive at a real monthly budget comparison, not just a gross-to-net figure.</p>

